{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600581/1930100801/0381.xml":{"full_text":"B-12\n$6,000 MATRIMONY\nFRAUDS HOLD FIVE\nPostal Authorities Told in\nIndiana Confession How\nPhotos Were Used.\nBr the Associated Press.\nINDIANAPOLIS, October B\u2014How an\nalleged fake matrimonial ting mulcted\nvictims throughout the South, Middle\nWest and West for more than $6,000\nwas revealed by Federal investigators\nyesterday following the arrest of five\npersons on charges of postal fraud.\nUsing photographs of two woman\nmembers of the ring as \u201cbait,\u201d the\nagency obtained sums ranging from a\nfew dollars to $1,700 from its victims,\npostal Inspectors said. Operations were\ncarried on from Dayton, Ohio; Muncie,\nInd.; Covington, Ky.; Marion, Ind.;\nLebanon, Ind., and Crawfordsville, Ind.,\nin turn, the Investigators revealed.\nArrests In Indiana.\nThose arrested are Miss Oda Llppens,\nat Marion; Timothy O\u2019Leary, alias\nRobert White; Ora Thomas, alias Roy\nGibbs, and Roxle Chaney Oibbs, at\nCrawfordsville, and Ethel Rose Brewer-\nWilliams, at Muncie.\nThe ring\u2019s operations were so exten\nsive that files of prospects were kept\nand a multiple-copy machine was used\nfor \"come-on\u201d letters. Details of the\nplan were made public by Inspector A.\nS. Kelly of Muncie and B. F. Simcoke\nof Lafayette. Ind.. who investigated.\nA confession by O\u2019Leary at Craw\nfordsville outlined how the agency ob\ntained money from matrimonial pros\npects. No requests for money were\nmade until the fifth letter, he said, and\nthose abrupt clients who wished to get,,\nmarried Immediately were dropped as\ntoo likely to cause trouble.\n$1,700 Paid by One.\nAmong the victims, according to\nO\u2019Leary\u2019s confession, were Charles\nGruth, El Reno. Okla., said to have paid\nMiss Llppens $1,700 on her hard-luck 1\nstories and requests for traveling ex\npenses; Nick Bouylas, Chicago; Joe\nGerl, Detroit, Mich.; Herbert Clawson,\nJamestown, N. Dak.: J. L. Miller,\nOwensville, Mo.; Andrew Haukedahl.\nCalmar, Iowa; Fred Hibbs, Long Beach,\nCalif.; Herman Sauers, Benavides. Tex.,\nand Victor Jacobellls, De Funiak\nSprings, Fla. In addition, O\u2019Leary said,\nthere was an Alabama postmaster who\nwrote his letters In poetry.\nThe prisoners will be brought to In\ndianapolis for arraignment In Federal\nCourt, Inspector Kelly said.\nBishop George Lewis Dies.\nINDEPENDENCE, Mo., October 8 (JP).\n\u2014George Lewis, 63, bishop of the Re\norganized Church of Jesus Christ of\nLatter Day Saints, is dead at his honfe\nIn Wallsend, New South Wales, Aus\ntralia, according to word received here\nyesterday by his son, George G. Lewis.\nBishop Lewis had been In charge of the\nchurch\u2019s Australian mission 25 years.\nLaNSBURCH'S\n\nextend heartfelt sympathy\nto the family of the late\nMorton H. Goldenberg\nLANSBURCH'S\nV 7th, Bth and E Sts.\u2014National 9800\nNo Connection With Any Other Store\nSo Warm\nand So Cute!\nWhen It's freezing and below. ro\nand Washington's very young and\ndecidedly discriminating clientele goes\nout to play in the snow they\u2019ll\nhe wearing one of these adorable\nbrushed wool sets from Lansburgh's.\nFour-Piece Brushed\nWool or Knit Sets\nWj *5-95\nA warm woolly\nI sweater, a pair of\nJj well fitting legging,\na snug little cap\nand a pair of cute\nV I J mittens\u2014of soft\nwool in white,\npink, blue or tan.\nJ J Sizes 1,2 and 3.\nj j lota\u2019 Vmt\u2014Ntrtk T\\\u2014t\nMakes Berlin Debut\nSILVIA LENT.\nSYLVIA LENT PLEASES\nHEARERS IN BERLIN DEBUT\nWashington Violinist Give\u00df Superb\nRendition of Ernest Bloch\u2019i\nSonata.\nBr the Associated Press.\nBERLIN. October 8. \u2014Sylvia Lent of\nWashington, D. C., at her Berlin musi\ncal debut last night played herself into\nthe hearts of her audience by a superb\nrendition of Ernest Bloch\u2019s violin\nsonata.\nHer performance of this brought her\nmany recalls.\nHer Interpretation of concertos by\nMozart and Saint-Saens was also much\napplauded.\nDIES IN 11-STORY FALL\nColumbia TJ. Law Student Plunges\nFrom Apartment Window.\nNEW YORK. October 8 (A*).\u2014 Milton\nLubell. 22-year-old law student at Co\nlumbia University, was killed last night\nin a* fall from an 11-story apartment\nIn East Ninety-sixth street.\nHis father and mother were in the\napartment at the time, but were not\naware of the youth's death until his\nbody was found in the courtyard.\nTelephone National\n5000\nFor immediate delivery of The\nStar to your home every evening\nand Sunday morning. The\nRoute Agent will collect at the\nend of each month, at the rate\nof 1% cents per day and 5 cents\nSunday.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., WEDNESDAY. OCTOBER 8. 1930.\nAUTO SEEN OASIS\nOF NEW WORLD ERA\nManufacturers\u2019 Association\nReport Says U. S. Has Taken\nLead in New Advance.\nBy the Associated Press.'\nNEW YORK, October B.\u2014The Na\ntional Associalton of manufacturers, in\nconvention here, was told by its Trade\nCommittee Monday that the develop\nment and utilization of automotive\nproducts here and abroad presaged \"an\nera of world enterprise scarce dreamed\nof before the World War\u201d and com\nparable to the expansion following in\nvention of the steam locomotive a cen\ntury ago.\n\u201cIn this development thfc United\nStates is prepared to take and is already\nNumber 2 of t series preceding a I\nW' wonderful celebration,\nII LANSBURGH\u2019S 70th ANNIVERSARY\nOut of Sight\nBut Not Out of Mind\nUjl \\\\7 E\u2019RE human after all. And we like to\nhe remembered. So when Uncle Sam\u2019*\nVfflTl postman stops at our door with letters ad\nJ jl'il dressed to Jane Stuart, your personal\n|P|)l shopper\u2014we love it.\n/I From Germany, France, Hawaii, Haiti,\n\\7 vj-A Porto Rico, and other far away place*\nv letters pour in almost daily.\nMrs. O. D., Berlin, Germany, wishes\nanother supply of toiletries. Mrs. E. W.\n_ T _ M., Haiti, wants more sheets\u2014just like\nthe last ones. Mrs. O. B. S., Hawaii,\n\u2019ZaV. wishes Jane